title: For Sale:  WALTHER P99C QA 40SW 3.5" W/2-8 ROUND MAGAZINES
postcontent:
Years ago, I was with a friend in the French Quarter in New Orleans when he asked a vendor the price of something. He was told, "If you have to ask, you can't afford it!" 
We've been using the term "rare" a lot the past six months to refer to guns that were easily obtainable last Fall. Everything has gotten harder to find. This pistols was NEVER easy to find and it's completely impossible now. I stumbled across it late one night on a supplier's web site and picked up immediately. 
There are a handful of P99C "AS" models out there, but I haven't seen a "QA" (Quick Action) in a very long time. 
This variant has a Glock style trigger system with a pre-loaded internal striker. When the trigger is pulled, the striker is fully cocked and released, firing the pistol. The trigger travel is approximately 8 mm (0.3 in) with a trigger pull of approximately 38 N (8.5 lbf). The trigger pull is consistent in length and force from the first shot to the last. The P99QA was announced in 2000 and discontinued in 2011. 
Get a new one now, it may be your last chance! It's already a collector's item.

Hello everyone I bought a few ar parts that i was planning to build an ar with but I have not had any money to finish the project. This is a very good barrel. I bought from AR15performance.com. This barrel is a .223 wylde barrel meaning it shoots both .223 Rem and 5.56. This is also melonite treated which is better that chrome lining it is easier to clean and it doesn't sacrifice loss of accuracy which chrome lining does. It has a 1 in 8 twist so you can shoot your lower gr. bullets to higher. A 1 in 7 twist stabilizes 62gr. and over well but sometimes not so well with 55gr which a 1 in 9 twist will do better, but a 1 in 9 twist doesn't stabilize 70gr. and over well so a 1 in 8 twist gives you best of both worlds. Finally it has a 5R polygonal pattern inside so the bullet shoots better down this barrel and sticks to the grooves better to make it shoot straighter. You can check out Ar15performance.com to see what I am talking about.
